182 to 192 Hudson Street, at, adjoining and north of the N.E. corner of Vestry Street. Nos. 188, 190, and 192 are frame houses with brick fronts. These buildings were later demolished and on their site was erected the 12-story Green Terminal Building. Also shown are tracks and cars of the New York Central Railroad. About 1900.

Brown Brothers.

182 to 186 Hudson Street, at, adjoining and north of the N.E. corner of Vestry Street. Also shown (right) are Nos. 24 to 18 and 16-12 Vestry Street, adjoining and east of the N.E. corner of Hudson Street. Nos. 24 to 18 are a row of 2½- story frame houses with brick fronts. These dwellings were demolished and is now (1937) a portion of the site of the Green Terminal Building.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

189 to 195 and 205 to 211 Hudson Street, west side, north from but not including Vestry, across Desbrosses, to and including Canal Streets. The 4-story structure (No. 195) at the S.W. corner of Desbrosses Street is on the site of the Leonard Lispenard House where Washington was entertained in 1775. On the opposite corner (N.W.) are two 2½-story frame house with brick fronts. This is a set of three views; No. two showing the lower stories of Nos. 189 to 193; No. three, Nos. 191 and 193; the latter two being between Vestry and Desbrosses Street. December 1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Hudson Street, west side, north from Vestry Street. Also shown is a sentry box, used by the flagman of the New York Central Railroad at the S.E. corner of Vestry Street.

December 20, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

184 to 204 Hudson Street, east side, north from but not including Vestry, to and including Canal Streets. Nos. 188 to 198 (six houses beginning with the 3-story white one on the right) are frame houses with brick fronts. All the buildings were razed in approximately 1928, and on their site was erected the Green Terminal Building, a 12-story structure. The tracks seen are those of the New York Central Railroad. Prior to 1930.
